UI/UX Assessment — OVERWATCH
Overall UX Rating: 7.0 / 10
Competent, functional, and honest — but not beautiful, not delightful, and not pushing the boundaries of what Streamlit can do.

What Works Well
1. Information architecture is strong (8/10)

Brief → Overview → Control Room → Detail pages is a proper progressive disclosure hierarchy
lazy_sections solves the Streamlit tab performance problem correctly (renders only active section)
Deep-link support via ?section=<slug> means users can bookmark specific views
Scope chips persist below the header so context survives scrolling
2. Honesty as a UX principle (9/10)

"Not configured" instead of invented budget numbers
Source + freshness captions on every panel
Truncation banners when results are capped
"Live fallback (bounded)" labels when reading from ACCOUNT_USAGE directly
This is rare. Most dashboards hide their uncertainty. This one surfaces it.
3. Data tables are well-handled (7.5/10)

_auto_formats applies convention-based formatting ($ for USD columns, commas for counts) without per-table config
Status columns get semantic colors automatically via status_columns_in + status_css
Every table has a CSV download button — auditors and managers love this
selectable_table enables row-click drill-through where Streamlit supports it
4. Chart system is cohesive (7/10)

Custom Altair theme with consistent palette (_ACCENT, _GRID, _LABEL)
Dollar-formatted axes, proper tooltips
sparkline_row for inline trends is a good addition
event_timeline for incident correlation is visually effective
waterfall_usd for attribution is the right chart type
hour_heatmap for time-of-day patterns
5. Error states are designed, not afterthoughts (8/10)

guard() handles: error → labeled error; empty → labeled info; truncated → warning banner
safe_page boundary means a crash never shows a Python traceback
Missing migration state surfaces a helpful message, not a blank page
What Doesn't Work
1. Visual design is utilitarian, not polished (5/10)

The theme is 48 lines of CSS. That's deliberate minimalism, but the result is:

st.metric cards with a subtle border are fine but generic — indistinguishable from any Streamlit demo
No visual weight differentiation between critical and informational sections
No custom typography hierarchy — everything uses Streamlit defaults
The "OVERWATCH" kicker at 0.72rem with letter-spacing is the only brand moment
The glowing cyan dot (.ow-brand-dot) is a nice touch but it's the only custom visual element
Verdict: Looks like a well-organized prototype, not a polished product. An executive seeing this for the first time will think "internal tool," not "platform."

2. Navigation is functional but flat (6/10)

Sidebar radio buttons for pages — works, but no visual indication of "where I am" beyond the selected radio
No breadcrumbs, no "you are here" context beyond scope chips
lazy_sections renders as a horizontal radio — this is a Streamlit limitation, but it means 7-8 sections render as a cramped pill bar on narrower screens
No keyboard navigation / shortcuts for power users
The jump box (sidebar search) is mentioned in FEATURES.md but I didn't see its implementation — if it exists, good; if not, navigation across 40+ sections requires knowing which page holds what
3. Color system is good but inconsistent in application (6.5/10)

status_colors.py is excellent — proper dark/light theme pairs, semantic meaning, contrast-aware. But:

Page icons still use emoji (☀️📊🎛️💰🔧🚨🔐⚙️) which render inconsistently across platforms
The chart accent color (#38bdf8 sky blue) doesn't clearly connect to severity — a spend chart and an info chip use the same blue
No color for "things are getting better" vs "things are getting worse" in KPI deltas beyond Streamlit's built-in green/red delta_color
4. Mobile experience is accidental, not designed (4/10)

The Brief page is described as "phone-friendly" but:

Streamlit's st.columns collapses columns on narrow viewports, which means KPI rows stack vertically — acceptable but not optimized
lazy_sections horizontal radio overflows on mobile
No responsive chart sizing — fixed height=260 means charts are either too tall on mobile or too short on desktop
No touch-friendly interaction patterns
Download buttons below every table add vertical noise on small screens
5. Information density swings between sparse and overwhelming (5.5/10)

Brief page: perfect density — 5 figures, fires, asks, done
Overview: good — KPI row, chart, score, actions
Control Room: good — pulse, queue, movers, freshness
Cost page (8 sections): too much. Each section is individually reasonable, but toggling through 8 radio pills to find what you need is a content management problem, not a UX solution
Operations (7 sections): same issue
No visual grouping/hierarchy within sections — every section looks the same (subheader → data → caption)
6. Interactivity is limited by Streamlit (6/10)

This isn't entirely the author's fault — Streamlit is a constrained framework. But:

No hover states or contextual menus
Row selection → drill is the only interactive pattern (and only works on newer Streamlit versions)
Filters are global (sidebar) but some sections ignore some filters — there's no visual feedback about which filters apply to the current section
No inline editing (alert thresholds require navigating to Admin)
No undo for operator actions
