Bottom Line
The UX is honest, well-structured, and functional — which puts it ahead of 90% of internal Streamlit dashboards. The information architecture (Brief → Overview → Detail) is genuinely good. The error/empty/truncation handling is best-in-class for Streamlit apps.

But it's constrained by two things:

Streamlit's framework limits — no custom widgets, no real-time updates, no rich interaction beyond dataframe selection
Minimal investment in visual design — 48 lines of CSS for an enterprise platform is too little. The status color system shows the author can think about visual design — they just haven't applied that thinking to layout, spacing, card design, or visual hierarchy at the page level.
If this were a portfolio piece going to leadership: the architecture impresses, the UX doesn't. The fix isn't a redesign — it's 20-30 hours of visual polish: card variants, severity indicators, consistent iconography, and information density optimization on the two most-visited pages (Brief and Control Room).
